    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="185"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d185">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">511.3B1/15</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The British Chargé</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lindsay</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-01-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 22, 1920</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 51</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: With reference to previous correspondence on the
                    subject of the Arms Traffic Convention, I have the honour to inform you that I
                    have received a communication from my Government stating that they propose in
                    the future to inform the Japanese Government whenever they request a
                    non-signatory Power to sign the Convention or to give a guarantee to observe its
                    conditions and whenever they receive notification that a guarantee has been
                    given or the Convention signed.</p>
                <p>His Majesty’s Government express the hope that the United States Government will
                    adopt similar measures.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">R. C. Lindsay</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
